{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:25:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12352"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12352"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.12,0.18,0.48,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4873"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51565"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4873"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12352"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36870"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"7940"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7865"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8338"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14826"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14840"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42744"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51565","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51565"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of a left-sided facial rash. She works as a childcare educator. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and asthma. Her regular medications include insulin and salbutamol as needed. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 120/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 38.1\u00b0C. She has a red, shiny, raised rash on her nose and left cheek, with a well-demarcated edge and irregular margins.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contact dermatitis","Rosacea","Shingles","Erysipelas","Slapped cheek syndrome"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture is most consistent with a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Eerysipelas\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is caused by a Streptococcus infection, typically developing over approximately 48 hours. Erysipelas is characterised by a red, shiny, raised, spreading plaque with a well-demarcated edge. The face and lower legs are the most frequently affected areas. Predisposing factors include an immunocompromised state, arteriovenous insufficiency, and lymphoedema. In this case, the patient\u0027s diabetes mellitus is a significant risk factor due to its effects on the immune system and peripheral circulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Econtact dermatitis,\u003C/strong\u003E the skin changes ranges from erythema, scaling, and oedema, vesiculation or severe swelling with bullae. Changes often occur in a pattern or distribution that can suggest a specific exposure, such as linear streaking on an arm or leg for external allergens or circumferential erythema. This pattern is not consistent with the well-demarcated facial rash described in this patient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERosacea\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by facial flushing, persistent erythema, telangiectasia, inflammatory papules, pustules, and oedema. While it can affect the cheeks and nose, it typically does not present with a sudden onset, well-demarcated edge, or fever as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EShingles\u003C/strong\u003E (herpes zoster) causes a painful rash with burning, tingling, and itching in a dermatomal distribution. It typically affects one side of the body or face, but the rash is vesicular rather than the shiny, raised appearance described here. Additionally, shingles is more common in individuals over 50 or those with weakened immune systems.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESlapped cheek syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (fifth disease) is a viral infection caused by parvovirus B19. While it can cause bright red cheeks in children, adults rarely develop the facial rash. Instead, they may experience joint pain and swelling. The sudden onset, fever, and well-demarcated rash in this case are more indicative of erysipelas than slapped cheek syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s presentation with a sudden onset of a well-demarcated, red, shiny, raised rash on the face, accompanied by fever and her history of diabetes (a predisposing factor), erysipelas is the most likely diagnosis. Treatment typically involves systemic antibiotics targeting Streptococcus, such as penicillin or a cephalosporin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erysipelas is characterised by a sudden onset of a red, shiny, raised rash with well-demarcated edges, commonly affecting the face and lower limbs.","Erysipelas is caused by Streptococcus infection and is more common in individuals with compromised immunity or vascular insufficiency.","Diabetes mellitus is a predisposing factor for erysipelas due to its effects on the immune system and peripheral circulation."],"references":["Michael Y, Shaukat NM. Erysipelas. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36870"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12352"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36870"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-26T20:15:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-26T20:15:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4873"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51565"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","i